LAUNCH
  Fire missiles or launch satellites.

SYNTAX
  launch <plane-spec> <target-x,y> [y|n]
  lnch   <plane-spec> <target-x,y> [y|n]

DESCRIPTION
  Launches missiles at a target sector, or puts satellite-capable
  planes into orbit over a target sector. <plane-spec> accepts a
  uid, a uid range, a comma list, "*", "~" (planes with no wing
  assigned), or a single letter naming a wing (see 'info wingadd').

  Only missile-type or satellite-type planes can be launched — check
  a plane's type with 'show plane b' or 'plane <uid>'.

  MISSILES are destroyed on use (one-shot). Damage to the target
  sector's efficiency scales with the missile's own efficiency
  (roughly effic*2%, capped at 100%).

  SATELLITES are not destroyed — they enter orbit and stay there.
  The trailing [y|n] argument is REQUIRED for a satellite launch:
  "y" for geostationary orbit (stays fixed over the target), "n" for
  a moving orbit. It's ignored for missile launches.

  Launching a satellite can fail outright (a chance that increases
  the lower the plane's efficiency — "KABOOOOM! Range safety officer
  detonates booster!", plane destroyed) or drift one hex off target
  (chance decreases with higher tech and efficiency). A successful
  launch reports how many time units until the satellite is ready —
  it needs to fully regenerate its mobility first (same passive
  regen every plane gets each update; no special action needed, just
  wait). Once ready, use 'satellite' to get a report from it.

  Requirements to launch a satellite:
    - Not already in orbit
    - At least 40% efficiency
    - Target within the plane's range

KNOWN GAPS (v1)
  - No fuel/petrol consumption check for either missiles or
    satellites (the underlying per-mission fuel mechanic isn't wired
    up anywhere in empire5 yet, not just here).
  - No airbase-readiness check before launch (4.4.1 requires the
    plane be at a valid airfield/carrier; empire5 doesn't verify this).
  - Anti-satellite missiles (shooting down an enemy's orbiting
    satellite) aren't implemented.

EXAMPLE
  launch 5 -4,2             fire missile (plane 5) at sector -4,2
  launch 10 0,0 y           launch satellite (plane 10), geostationary
  launch 10 0,0 n           launch satellite (plane 10), moving orbit

